<h1 class=3D"post-title">Fundamentals of Radiance Cascades</h1><span class=
=3D"post-sub"> 2024-10-22&nbsp;=E2=80=A2&nbsp;3815 words&nbsp;=E2=80=A2&nbs=
p;20 min&nbsp;=E2=80=A2&nbsp;Max &lt;mxcop&gt; </span><h2 id=3D"introductio=
n">Introduction</h2><p>In this article I'm going to share my understanding =
of the fudamentals of Radiance Cascades. <em>(abbreviated as RC)</em><br da=
ta-filtered=3D"filtered"> Over the past months I've build some <span class=
=3D"highlight">intuitions</span> &amp; understanding of RC, and my goal is =
to share some of that here with you.</p><p>This article will likely be easi=
er to follow for those with <span class=3D"highlight">prior experience</spa=
n> with ray tracing &amp; global illumination.<br data-filtered=3D"filtered=
"> Nevertheless, I'll do my best to explains everything in an intuitive way=
 using <span class=3D"highlight">graphics</span>!</p><p>At it's core, Radia=
nce Cascades is a method for efficiently representing a <span class=3D"high=
light">radiance field</span> <em>(light field)</em>.<br data-filtered=3D"fi=
ltered"> Which allows us to represent the <span class=3D"highlight">incomin=
g light</span> from/around some area at any point within that area.<br data=
-filtered=3D"filtered"> <em>In 2D that area is usually the screen.</em></p>=
<blockquote><p>For the sake of simplicity I will explain everything in 2D, =
however RC can be expanded into 3D aswell.</p></blockquote><p>So, what can =
RC in 2D <em>(also referred to as Flatland)</em> achieve?<br data-filtered=
=3D"filtered"> My implementation is able to compute <span class=3D"highligh=
t">diffuse global illumination</span> in real-time:</p><div class=3D"video"=
><video class=3D"video" loop=3D"" muted=3D"" playsinline=3D"" style=3D"widt=
h:640px" controls=3D""><source src=3D"https://m4xc.dev/anim/articles/fundam=
ental-rc/showcase.mp4" type=3D"video/mp4" data-filtered=3D"filtered"> Video=
 tag is not supported.</video><i>Diffuse global illumination in flatland.</=
i></div><p>An awesome property of this method is that this is done <span cl=
ass=3D"highlight">fully-deterministically</span>!<br data-filtered=3D"filte=
red"> Furthermore, there are already plenty of clever ways to get its perfo=
rmance to acceptable levels for modern hardware.</p><p><em>So without furth=
er ado, let's dive in!</em></p><hr><h2 id=3D"observations">Observations</h2=
><p>Radiance Cascades is built on <strong>two</strong> key observations.<br=
 data-filtered=3D"filtered"> So first, let's observe these together, and ha=
ve a <span class=3D"highlight">short recap</span> afterwards.</p><p>But, be=
fore we observe anything I want clear up what I mean with the following <sp=
an class=3D"highlight">terms</span>:</p><ol><li><span class=3D"highlight">r=
adiance</span>: light from a specific direction, at a specific point. <em>(=
You can think of this as a ray)</em></li><li><span class=3D"highlight">irra=
diance</span>: light from a subset of directions, at a specific point. <em>=
(You can think of this as light from all directions)</em></li></ol><blockqu=
ote><p>Because radiance is just one direction, we can build irradiance from=
 a bunch of directions <em>(radiance)</em>.</p></blockquote><h3 id=3D"angul=
ar-observation">Angular Observation</h3><div class=3D"video"><video class=
