ecreases.<br data-filtered=3D"filtered"> Because we need higher resolution =
for both in order to resolve the smallest object in the scene.</p><h3 id=3D=
"recap">Recap</h3><p>Ok, these <span class=3D"highlight">observations</span=
> took me some time to <em>wrap my head around</em> but they're key to unde=
rstanding RC.<br data-filtered=3D"filtered"> <em>So let's quickly reiterate=
 our observations.</em></p><p>What we've <span class=3D"highlight">observed=
</span> is that the <strong>further</strong> we are from the closest object=
 in the scene:</p><ol><li>The <strong>less</strong> spatial resolution we n=
eed. <em>(e.g. the <span class=3D"highlight">larger spacing</span> can be b=
etween probes)</em></li><li>The <strong>more</strong> angular resolution we=
 need. <em>(e.g. the <span class=3D"highlight">more rays</span> we need per=
 probe)</em></li></ol><hr><h2 id=3D"exploiting-observations">Exploiting Obs=
ervations</h2><p>Now that we've made the observations and defined the penum=
bra theorem, let's look at how we can <span class=3D"highlight">exploit</sp=
an> these observations.</p><h3 id=3D"angular">Angular</h3><p>We've got a <s=
trong>problem</strong>: classic probes we're all used to, can hit objects a=
t <span class=3D"highlight">virtually any distance</span>.<br data-filtered=
=3D"filtered"> In order to exploit the <span class=3D"highlight">penumbra t=
heorem</span> we need some way to <em>narrow</em> this possible <span class=
=3D"highlight">distance window</span>.</p><div class=3D"video"><video class=
=3D"video" loop=3D"" muted=3D"" playsinline=3D"" style=3D"width:360px" cont=
rols=3D""><source src=3D"https://m4xc.dev/anim/articles/fundamental-rc/spli=
tting-anim.mp4" type=3D"video/mp4" data-filtered=3D"filtered"> Video tag is=
 not supported.</video><i>Figure D: Probe being split into =E2=80=9Crings=
=E2=80=9D.</i></div><p><em>Figure D</em>, shows one way of narrowing this w=
indow, we can discretize our circular probes into rings.<br data-filtered=
=3D"filtered"> By doing this we <strong>not only</strong> know that each ri=
ng will hit within a narrow distance window,<br data-filtered=3D"filtered">=
 we can also <span class=3D"highlight">vary</span> the <span class=3D"highl=
ight">angular resolution</span> between rings!</p><blockquote><p>These new =
rays with a limited range, are referred to as <strong>intervals</strong>.</=
p></blockquote><p>This is exactly what we're looking for to <span class=3D"=
highlight">exploit</span> the <span class=3D"highlight">angular part</span>=
 of the penumbra theorem.<br data-filtered=3D"filtered"> We can increase th=
e interval count <em>(aka, decrease the angle between rays)</em> with each =
consecutive ring that hits objects further away.</p><div class=3D"img"><img=
 alt=3D"Figure E: Increasing angular resolution for more distant =E2=80=9Cr=
ings=E2=80=9D." title=3D"Figure E: Increasing angular resolution for more d=
istant =E2=80=9Crings=E2=80=9D." src=3D"https://m4xc.dev/img/articles/funda=
mental-rc/inc-angular-split.png" width=3D"360px"><i>Figure E: Increasing an=
gular resolution for more distant =E2=80=9Crings=E2=80=9D.</i></div><p>In o=
rder to still <span class=3D"highlight">capture</span> our entire scene, we=
 will have many of these <em>rings</em>.</p><p>In the example in <em>Figure=
 E</em>, we increase the interval count by <strong>2x</strong> with every c=
onsecutive ring.<br data-filtered=3D"filtered"> Which let's us increase the=
 <span class=3D"highlight">distance window</span> of each ring <em>(the len=
gth of its intervals)</em> by that same factor.<br data-filtered=3D"filtere=
d"> This ensures the <span class=3D"highlight">gap</span> between intervals=
 remains <em>approximately</em> equal between rings.</p><h3 id=3D"spatial">=
Spatial</h3><p>So far, with the angular observation we haven't really achie=
ved any <span class=3D"highlight">reduction</span> in ray count.<br data-fi=
ltered=3D"filtered"> We're still casting a <span class=3D"highlight">very l=
arge number</span> of rays for each probe using this method, <em>good thing=
 that's about to change.</em></p><p>This is when we <span class=3D"highligh=
t">drop the idea</span> that these rings together make up a <strong>single<=
/strong> probe.<br data-filtered=3D"filtered"> Instead, let's view each con=
secutive ring as its own probe, which <em>can be moved</em>.</p><blockquote=
><p>From now on when we refer to <strong>probes</strong>, we are referring =
to <strong>rings</strong>.</p></blockquote><div class=3D"video"><video clas=
s=3D"video" loop=3D"" muted=3D"" playsinline=3D"" style=3D"width:360px" con=
trols=3D""><source src=3D"https://m4xc.dev/anim/articles/fundamental-rc/spa=
tial-exploit-anim.mp4" type=3D"video/mp4" data-filtered=3D"filtered"> Video=
 tag is not supported.</video><i>Figure F: Increasing probe/ring spacing.</=
i></div><blockquote><p>The length of the intervals in <em>Figure F</em> is =
<strong>incorrect</strong>, this is to make them easier on the eyes.</p></b=
lockquote><p><em>Figure F</em>, shows one way we can use this new <span cla=
ss=3D"highlight">perspective</span> on the probes.<br data-filtered=3D"filt=
ered"> We saw during the spatial observation that when objects are <span cl=
ass=3D"highlight">further away</span>, we can have <span class=3D"highlight=
">larger spacing</span> between probes.</p><p>So, when our <span class=3D"h=
ighlight">distance window</span> gets further and further away, we may incr=
ease the <span class=3D"highlight">spacing</span> between those probes.<br =
data-filtered=3D"filtered"> And because we're trying to fill some <span cla=
ss=3D"highlight">area</span> with them, this means we need less of them.</p=
><p>There is a visible <span class=3D"highlight">disconnect</span> between =
probes between cascades, this <em>does</em> result in artifacts, mainly <em=
>ringing</em>.</p><blockquote><p>There are fixes out there <em>(e.g. biline=
ar &amp; parallax fix)</em>, however they're out of the scope of this artic=
le.</p></blockquote><hr><h2 id=3D"cascades">Cascades</h2><p>Now that we und=
erstand how we can exploit the <strong>two</strong> key observations.<br da=
ta-filtered=3D"filtered"> Let's put the <strong>two</strong> together and f=
inally define what exactly a <span class=3D"highlight">cascade</span> is!</=
p><div class=3D"img2x1"><div class=3D"img"><img alt=3D"Figure G1: Cascade 0=
, with 4x4 probes." title=3D"Figure G1: Cascade 0, with 4x4 probes." src=3D=
"https://m4xc.dev/img/articles/fundamental-rc/cascade0.png" width=3D"360px"=
><i>Figure G1: Cascade 0, with 4x4 probes.</i></div><div class=3D"img"><img=
 alt=3D"Figure G2: Cascade 1, with 2x2 probes." title=3D"Figure G2: Cascade=
 1, with 2x2 probes." src=3D"https://m4xc.dev/img/articles/fundamental-rc/c=
ascade1.png" width=3D"360px"><i>Figure G2: Cascade 1, with 2x2 probes.</i><=
/div></div><p>A cascade is basically a <span class=3D"highlight">grid of pr=
obes</span>, in which all probes have <strong>equal</strong> properties.<br=
 data-filtered=3D"filtered"> <em>(e.g. interval count, interval length, pro=
be spacing)</em></p><p>The reason we call them cascades is because they <sp=
an class=3D"highlight">cascade outwards</span> with increasing interval cou=
nt and length.<br data-filtered=3D"filtered"> <em>Or at least, that's how I=
 like to think about it.</em></p><h3 id=3D"cascade-hierarchy">Cascade Hiera=
rchy</h3><p>A cascade <span class=3D"highlight">on its own</span> isn't sup=
er useful, only capturing a small part of the scene.<br data-filtered=3D"fi=
ltered"> Many cascades together is what we're really after, we want to <str=
ong>combine</strong> them into a hierarchy.<br data-filtered=3D"filtered"> =
For example in <em>Figure G1 &amp; G2</em> we can see two cascades that cou=
ld make up a <span class=3D"highlight">cascade hierarchy</span>.</p><p>Most=
 of the time, for <span class=3D"highlight">simplicity</span> sake we will =
decrease probe count between cascades by <strong>2x</strong> along each axi=
s.<br data-filtered=3D"filtered"> Like we've seen also in <em>Figure G1 &am=
p; G2</em>, we will find out why this is convenient <em>later</em> on in th=
is article.</p><p>If we're following the <span class=3D"highlight">penumbra=
 condition</span>, the spatial and angular resolution should be <strong>inv=
ersely proportional</strong>.<br data-filtered=3D"filtered"> So if we incre=
ase probe spacing by <strong>2x</strong> we need to decrease the angle betw=
een intervals by <strong>2x</strong> as well.</p><blockquote><p>However, th=
ere's also many implementation which decrease the angle between intervals b=
y <strong>4x</strong> instead.<br data-filtered=3D"filtered"> It is more co=
stly, but it may produce higher quality results in some cases.</p></blockqu=
ote><h3 id=3D"cascade-memory">Cascade Memory</h3><div class=3D"video"><vide=
