g> interval.</p><blockquote><p>We also merge the visibility terms, by multi=
plying them a hit will also be carried downwards. <em>(1.0 * 0.0 =3D 0.0)</=
em></p></blockquote><h3 id=3D"merging-cones">Merging Cones</h3><p>It would =
be <span class=3D"highlight">really expensive</span> if we had to merge thr=
ough each cascade for each possible direction.<br data-filtered=3D"filtered=
"> So instead, let's merge each cascade into the one below it, from the <sp=
an class=3D"highlight">top down</span>.</p><div class=3D"img"><img alt=3D"F=
igure K: Cone made out of intervals." title=3D"Figure K: Cone made out of i=
ntervals." src=3D"https://m4xc.dev/img/articles/fundamental-rc/interval-con=
e.png" width=3D"360px"><i>Figure K: Cone made out of intervals.</i></div><p=
>Because we're trying to extract <span class=3D"highlight">diffuse lighting=
</span>, directional resolution isn't very important.<br data-filtered=3D"f=
iltered"> So it's completely fine to <em>squash</em> the entire scene radia=
nce into <strong>cascade0</strong> <em>(which has the lowest angular resolu=
tion)</em></p><p>Because we have a <span class=3D"highlight">branch factor<=
/span>, e.g. <strong>4x</strong>, each cascade we will merge <strong>4</str=
ong> intervals down into <strong>1</strong> interval.<br data-filtered=3D"f=
iltered"> Doing so for all cascades <span class=3D"highlight">recursively</=
span> captures the radiance from a cone, as shown in <em>Figure K</em>.</p>=
<p>This is perfect for capturing our <span class=3D"highlight">low angular =
resolution</span> diffuse lighting!</p><h3 id=3D"merging-spatially">Merging=
 Spatially</h3><p>Not only our angular resolution changes between cascades,=
 we also know our spatial resolution changes.<br data-filtered=3D"filtered"=
